problems.description: See if you can select the correct line of code to place the value 2 in the variable x. Just slide the correct line of code from the options to the solutions box.
problems.examples: In Java you can store numbers and other values in variables, like this "int x = 2;". This means to assign the value 2 to the integer x.
problems.name: First Variable

problems.description: Try to place the value 5 in to the variable x. You have to declare x (state its type and, optionally, give it an initial value).
problems.examples: You can also add a number to a variable and then assign the result to the original variable rather than to a different variable.
problems.name: Assigning Results

problems.description: For this problem, try to select the 2 lines of code that will assign the number 1 to the variable x and the string "hi" to the variable y.
problems.examples: Java is strictly typed, which means that you have to specify what data type a variable will be before you assign a value to it. For instance, you have to declare x as an integer or a string before you assign values to it: String x = 'hello'; or int x = 2;.
problems.name: Two Variables

problems.description: See if you can get the value 5 into the variable z using these lines of code.
problems.examples: Variables are helpful when doing Math. You can add numbers to variables and then assign the result to another variable.
problems.name: Adding Numbers

problems.description: In this problem, try to place the value 2 in the variable x by subtracting other numbers and variables from x.
problems.examples: You can subtract from variables as well
problems.name: Subtracting

problems.description: Here is a more interesting example of subtracting. In this problem, try to place the value 5 in the variable z by subtracting other variables from z.
problems.examples: Math is an important skill for programmers. Try using algebra techniques to get the desired result. Remember to initialize all the variables before you proceed though!
problems.name: More Subtracting

problems.description: You can multiply numbers using the * operator. Try to assign the value 10 to the variable x.
problems.examples:
Hope you haven't forgotten your multiplication tables. 
Once you assign a new value to a variable than what it was created with, it takes up the new value.
problems.name: Multiplying

problems.description: You can divide numbers by using the / operator. Place the value 3 in the variable y.
problems.examples: Again, initialize the variable before assigning a value to it which you can use.
problems.name: Division

problems.description: The % (modulo) operator can be used to find the remainder of dividing one number by another. Place the value 3 in the variable x.
problems.examples: For example: 5 % 2 = 1 because 1 is the remainder of dividing 5 by 2.
problems.name: Modulo

problems.description: Using the % (modulo) operator, place the value 1 in the variable x and the value 3 in the variable y.
problems.examples:
Hurray!! You've reached the last problem. Use those smart brains of yours and you're done with the first level.
Once a variable changes its value, the next time it is used, the newer value will be used.
problems.name: More Modulo
